sec.p:
In this study, we perform the first direct comparison of multi-echo T2 relaxation (GRASE) and steady-state (mcDESPOT) myelin imaging in both the brain and cervical spinal cord in a cohort of healthy participants. Our comparison is supplemented with data in the context of demyelinating disease pathology, analyzed on an individual basis for people with multiple sclerosis. The goals of this study are to:
create atlases of normative reference MWF and fM values for both brain and cervical spinal cord;
use atlas-based methods to compare myelin imaging approaches with minimal influence from biological variation and measurement noise;
improve characterisation of the relationship between MWF and fM, by comparing values across a diverse range of tissue, including healthy and diseased brain and spinal cord.
